To simplify this trigonometric expression, we can start by finding a common denominator.
\end{think} 
The common denominator of the two fractions is $\cos x(1+\sin x)$.  We use the Distributive Property to multiply this expression out.
\end{think} 
\[\cos x + \cos x\sin x\]
\end{think}
Now, we can rationalize the numerator with the conjugate.
\end{think}
\[\dfrac{\cos x(1-\sin x)}{1-\sin^2 x}\]
\end{think}
Since $\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1$, we can simplify the denominator to get
\end{think}
\[\dfrac{\cos x(1-\sin x)}{\cos^2 x}\]
\end{think}
Canceling a single $\cos x$, we get
\end{think}
\[\dfrac{1-\sin x}{\cos x}\]
\end{think}
We then move forward, denesting.  We divide the numerator and denominator by $\cos x$.
\end{think}
\[\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{\cos x}-\dfrac{\sin x}{\cos x}}{1}\]
\end{think}
We recognize that $\dfrac{1}{\cos x} = \sec x$ and $\dfrac{\sin x}{\cos x} = \tan x$.
\end{think}
We are done.  But just in case someone is curious, we have
\end{think}
\[\sec x - \tan x\]
\end{think}
